a4e590ce-f19f-4a64-a91e-abd214a717b6.051e0140-d32a-449a-85bb-3a36943dc44d.description=
Updates values of a change ticket.

Inputs\:
host - The DNS name or IP Address of your Service Manager host
port - The port to connect to your Service Manager host on.
protocol - The protocol to connect to your Service Manager host with. Either HTTP or HTTPS.
username - The username for the Service Manager host. The user should have only a sysadmin profile (falcon, on a default SM installation).
password - The password for the Service Manager user.
smVersion - Version of Service Manager. If the given value is empty or contains only spaces the default version 'sm93x' will be used.
actualCost - Actual cost
approvalStatus - Change approval status
assignee - Assignee of ticket
assignmentGroup - Primary assignment group. This input is required on versions beginning with SM7.10.
assets - Assets (sometimes interchangeable with Configuration Item)
briefDescription - Brief description (one-line); corresponds to "Title" in SM interface for SM 7.1x or newer.
configItem - Configuration item (sometimes interchangeable with Configuration Item)
contact - Contact for the ticket
coordinator - Coordinator
description - Ticket description
estimateDescription - Cost estimate description
estimatePrice - Cost estimate
initialImpact - Initial impact (eg. 1,2,3,4).
journalUpdates - Update history (new-line delimited)
location - the location for the change, starting with SM version 7.10.  
misc1 - mapped to "Change Tester" in SM interface
misc2 - mapped to "Testing results (pass ot fail)" in SM interface
misc3 - mapped to "Brief Description" in SM interface
open - Open the ticket?
plannedEndDate - Planned end date/time. 
plannedStartDate - Planned start date/time.
priority - Ticket priority (eg. 1,2,3)
reason - Reason for action / change. Please choose one of the value listed below.    
    problem (means Incident/Problem Resolution)
    user (means User Dissatisfaction)
    configuration (means New Configuration Item)
    upgrade (means Proposed Upgrade)
    business (means Business Requirement)
    legislation (means Legislation)
    vendor (means Vendor Product/Service Change)
    unplanned (means Unplanned Change Detection)

requestedBy - Ticket requester
requestedEndDate - Requested end date by initiator. This input is required on versions beginning with SM7.10.
riskAssessment - A value representing the risk assessment
service - Affected service with ticket. This input is required on versions beginning with SM7.10.
severity -  Severity (sometimes called User Priority).
subCategory - Subcategory / area. 
scheduledOutageStart - Scheduled outage start date/time.
scheduledOutageEnd - Scheduled outage end date/time. 
id - ID of the ticket

Fields below should be assigned a value only when updating a change in SM 9.30 with Process Designer Content Package installed\:
actualOutageStart - Actual Downtime Start
actualOutageEnd - Actual Downtime End
implementationStart - Actual Implementation Start
implementationEnd - Actual Implementation End
backOutComments - Backout Comments
backoutMethod - Backout Method
backOutPlan - Backout plan
buildTestPlan - Build and Test Plan
buildTestResult - Build and Test Result
changeModel - Change Model
changeOwner - Change Owner
effectOfNotImplementing - Effect Of Not Implementing
extProjectRef - External Reference
implemenationComments - Implementation Comments
implementationPlan - Implementation Plan
reviewResults - Review Results

Responses\:
success - The operation completed successfully.
failure - Something went wrong.

Returns\:
smMessage - Service Manager request brief message
smMessages - Service manager request additional messages
smReturnCode - Service Manager request's return code
smStatus - Service Manager request return status

Notes\:
The values for the inputs should be the ones permitted by Service Manager. The allowed values can be found in the corresponding underlying database.

The value for the date inputs should be provided in one of the following forms\: mm/dd/yyyy hh\:mm\:ss GMT or mm/dd/yyyy GMT (for example, 03/12/14 01\:41\:27 UTC or 03/12/14 UTC), otherwise an unparsable date error is obtained. 

In some of the cases the operation can indicate misleading responses, meaning that even though the operation failed, the field was updated or the other way around. This is a problem related to Service Manager's response and cannot be influenced.
a4e590ce-f19f-4a64-a91e-abd214a717b6.14d9f176-42c6-4bca-a627-d4fc8b8365e6.callout=Create Service Manager Incident in the event a failure occurs during the VM provisioning process. Details are captured from the previous processes are collected and populated in the description in the incident. a4e590ce-f19f-4a64-a91e-abd214a717b6.1a3e23c9-d4e1-4375-b97e-bd3d01c07b4e.prompt=Select Storage Capacity\: a4e590ce-f19f-4a64-a91e-abd214a717b6.348e9647-0e5c-440a-91fa-8483c42b2744.prompt=Description a4e590ce-f19f-4a64-a91e-abd214a717b6.3c02bc57-d3e5-4c23-a823-6eee36613166.prompt=Select Memory\: a4e590ce-f19f-4a64-a91e-abd214a717b6.4571b5c0-1386-4e48-94c6-2ca80a827fee.description=
This flow sends, stores or displays a notification message according to your notification type selection. You can use this flow to select how to be notified about the outcome of other flows. 

Inputs\:
    notifyData -  The content of the notification message.
    notifyMethod - The notification type. This value is not case sensitive.
Valid values\: Write to File, Email, Display or None
    subject - A summary of the notification content. 
    destination - The destination of the notification. You must specify a value for this input if "notifyMethod" is set to ‘Email’ or ‘Write to File’.
Valid values\: An email address or a file name
    notificationServer - The email server used to send the notification email message. If "notifyMethod" is set to ‘Email’, you must specify a value for this input.
    from - The email address of the sender of the notification email message.  If "notifyMethod" is set to ‘Email’, you must specify a value for this input.
    serverPort - The notification service’s server port. This field’s value is used when the "notifyMethod" is ‘Email’, but it is optional.
Default value\: 25
    htmlEmail - The value should be true if the email is in rich text/HTML format. The value should be false to send the email in plain text format.
Default value\: true

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Note\:
    To schedule a flow that uses this flow, you need to supply all the required fields for the used notification method. For example, if "notifyMethod" is set to ‘File’, the "destination" input must also be specified.

Examples\:
    This is a valid input example for storing a notification message to a file\:
      notifyData\: notificationContent
      notifyMethod\: Write to File
      subject\: notificationSubject
      destination\: C\:\Program File\notification.txt
a4e590ce-f19f-4a64-a91e-abd214a717b6.4997cf6c-c6fc-424e-86e3-99ee00bbc36e.prompt=Virtual Machine name\: a4e590ce-f19f-4a64-a91e-abd214a717b6.4b050881-46a8-4793-adc0-b0c72aedcd15.description=Creates a new virtual machine in the vmFolder specified and attaches it to the resource pool specified. Required privilege for the user that runs this operation\: VirtualMachine.Inventory.Create Inputs\: host - VMWare host hostname or IP. user - VMWare username. password - VMWare user's password. port - Port to connect on. Examples\: 443, 80 protocol - Connection protocol Valid values\: https, http closeSession - Close the internally kept VMWare Infrastructure API session at completion of operation Valid values\: "true", "false" async - Asynchronously perform the task Valid values\: true, false taskTimeOut - Time to wait before the operation is considered to have failed (seconds). Default value\: 800 vmName - Virtual machine name being created (new). vmCpuCount - Number of virtual machine CPUs to setup. hostSystem - Target virtual machine host system. clusterName - Name of the VMWare HA or DRS cluster. description - Description / annotation. dataStore - Datastore or datastore cluster (eg. host\:dsname, mydatastore). guestOSID - Guest OS ID (eg. win95Guest,winNetEnterprise64Guest,etc.) or OS description (Microsoft Windows 3.1,Microsoft Windows Vista (64-bit),Red Hat Enterprise Linux 3 (64-bit)). A list of valid entries can be retrieved via the GetOSDescriptors operation. vmDatacenter - Virtual machine's datacenter. vmMemorySize - Virtual machine memory size (megabytes). vmResourcePool - Virtual machine's resource pool. vmFolder - Virtual machine's folder by inventory path, '/' delimited not including datacenter (eg. ManagedVMs/DRS/Location1). For root folder, use '/'. vmDiskSize - Size of the virtual disk to create (MB). thinProvision - Specify whether to perform thin provisioning of the virtual disk. If true, the disk format will be set as thin provisioned format. If false, the disk format will be set as thick format. Valid values\: "true", "false" Default Value\: "false" eagerZero - specify if the thick disk type (thinProvisioning input set to false) is eager zero or lazy zeroed. Data located on eager zeroed disks is zeroed out when the virtual disk is created. It migth take longer to create disks in this format Valid values\: "true", "false" Default Value\: "false" networkName - Name of the virtual machine's network or network port group. The value is case sensitive. If the input is empty, the virtual machine will be added to the first network found. version - The hardware version of the virtual machine. If the input is empty, VMware will assign a version to the VM based on the version of the ESX it is created on. Valid values\: "vmx-04", "vmx-07", "vmx-08", "vmx-09", "vmx-10", "vmx-11", "vmx-13" busSharing - Mode for sharing the SCSI bus. Valid values\:"physical", "virtual", "none". controllerType - The SCSI controller type. Valid values\:"BusLogic Parallel", "LSI Logic Parallel","LSI Logic SAS","VMware Paravirtual". connectionTimeout - The time to wait for a connection to be established, in seconds. A "connectionTimeout" value of '0' represents an infinite timeout. Default value\: 0 Format\: an integer representing seconds Examples\: 10, 20 socketTimeout - The time to wait for data (a maximum period of inactivity between two consecutive data packets), in seconds. A "socketTimeout" value of '0' represents an infinite timeout. Default value\: 0 Format\: an integer representing seconds Examples\: 10, 20 Results\: returnResult - Task result or operation result. Responses\: success - The operation completed successfully. failure - Something went wrong. Notes\: 1. Note that "socketTimeout" and "connectionTimeout" inputs do not represent the time to wait for the operation to complete. They are used when communicating with the service, to make sure that the service is up and responds to client's requests. They can be used for service diagnosis purpose. 2. The "taskTimeOut" input is only used when the task is performed in a synchronous manner ("async" is set to "false"). 3. There are some limitations based on the VM hardware version\: Virtual hardware 13 (vSphere 6.5)\: 128 CPU,6TB RAM, 62TB HDD Virtual hardware 11 (vSphere 6.0)\: 128 CPU,4TB RAM, 62TB HDD Virtual hardware 10 (vSphere 5.5)\: 64 CPU, 1TB RAM, 62TB HDD Virtual hardware 9 (vSphere 5.1)\: 64 CPU, 1TB RAM, 2TB HDD Virtual hardware 8 (vSphere 5)\: 32 CPU, 1TB RAM, 2TB HDD Virtual hardware 7 (vSphere 4)\: 8 CPU, 256GB RAM, 2TB HDD Virtual hardware 4 (ESX 3.x)\: 4 CPU, 64GB RAM, 2TB HDD Virtual hardware 3 (ESX 2.5)\: 2 CPU, 3600MB RAM, 2TB HDD 4. You must provide a value for either the clusterName or the hostSystem input, they are mutually exclusive. a4e590ce-f19f-4a64-a91e-abd214a717b6.51b154f2-6b52-4618-92e3-e6d171b461fa.prompt=Asynchronously Perform Task?\: a4e590ce-f19f-4a64-a91e-abd214a717b6.54dc6003-eaa8-4af4-8fad-55ef525650e1.prompt=Password\: a4e590ce-f19f-4a64-a91e-abd214a717b6.5609428a-f196-443d-b5e8-4637dfdc519a.description=
Create an incident ticket.

Inputs\:
host - The DNS name or IP Address of your Service Manager host.
port - The port to connect to your Service Manager host.
protocol - The protocol to connect to your Service Manager host. This value can be either HTTP or HTTPS.
username - The username for the Service Manager host.
password - The password for the Service Manager user.
smVersion - Version of Service Manager. If the value is empty or contains spaces only, the default version 'sm93x' will be used.
alertStatus - Alert status.
assignee - Assignee of the ticket. Maps to "Assignee Name" in SM 7.00, 7.01.
assignmentGroup - Assignment group of the ticket.  Maps to "Primary Assignment Group" in SM 7.00, 7.01 (This field is optional when creating a new incident in SM 9.3x with Process Designer Content Pack 9.30.3 installed, but is mandatory for all other versions).
briefDescription - Brief description (one-line). Maps to "Title" in SM 7.10,7.11,9.20,93x and "Incident title" in SM 7.01,7.00.
category - Ticket category.
closedBy - Ticket closer. Maps to "Closed" in SM 7.00, 7.01, 7.10, 7.11 ("History" tab).
closureCode - Ticket closure code. Maps to "Resolution Code" in SM 7.00, 7.01 ("Activities" tab).
configItem - Configuration item. Maps to "Affected CI" in SM 7.10, SM 7.11, SM9.20, SM9.3x and to "Affected Item" in SM 7.00, 7.01 ("CI's and Services" tab).
contact - Contact for the ticket. Not visible to user in the default view of an incident in SM 7.10, 7.11, 9.20, 9.3x.
description - Ticket description. Maps to "Incident Description" in SM 7.00, 7.01.
initialImpact - Initial impact (for example\: 1,2,3). Maps to "Impact" in SM 7.10, 7.11, 9.20, 9.3x and to "Initial Impact Assessment" in SM 7.00, 7.01.
journalUpdates - Update history (new-line delimited) in the "Activities" tab.
openedBy - Ticket opener. Maps to "Opened" in SM 7.00, 7.01, 7.10, 7.11 ("History" tab).
problemType - Problem type. Not visible to user in the default view of an incident in SM 7.10, 7.11, 9.20 and 9.3x. Required for SM 7.00 and 7.01, optional for SM 7.10, 7.11,  9.20 and 9.3x.
productType - Product type. Maps to "Sub-area" in SM 7.10, 7.11 and 9.20.  Maps to "Area" in SM 9.3x with Process Designer Content Pack 9.30.3 installed (This field is optional when creating a new incident in SM 9.3x with Process Designer Content Pack 9.30.3 installed, but is mandatory for all other versions).
resolution - Ticket resolution information. Maps to "Solution" in SM 7.00, 7.01, 7.10, 7.11, 9.20 and 9.3x.
resolutionFixType - Fix method for the ticket (permanent or temporary).  Not visible to user in the default view of an incident.
service - Affected service with ticket. Not available for SM 7.00, 7.01. 
severity - Severity (sometimes called User Priority). Maps to "Urgency" in SM 7.00, 7.01, 7.10, 7.11, 9.20 and 9.3x.
slaAgreementID - SLA Agreement ID. Not visible to user in the default view of an incident.
solution - Ticket solution. Not visible to user in the default view of an incident.
subCategory - Subcategory. Maps to "Area" in SM 7.10,7.11,9.20. Maps to "Subcategory" in SM 9.3x with Process Designer Content Pack 9.30.3 installed (This field is optional when creating a new incident in SM 9.3x with Process Designer Content Pack 9.30.3 installed, but is mandatory for all other versions).
ticketOwner - Ticket owner. Maps to "Owner" in SM 7.00, 7.01, 7.10, 7.11, 9.20, 9.3x.
updatedBy - User name of last updater. Maps to "Last updated" in SM 7.00, 7.01, 7.10, 7.11 ("History" tab).

Responses\:
success - The operation completed successfully.
failure - Error occurred.

Returns\:
smMessage - A brief message of a Service Manager request.
smMessages - Additional messages of a Service manager request.
smReturnCode - The return code of a Service Manager request.
smStatus - The return status of a Service Manager request.
id - Ticket ID.

Note\:
Refer to the following steps on the SM 7.00/7.01 client to view a list of recommended values for siteCategory\:
1. From the System Navigator, click Tailoring > Forms Designer.
2. In the Form field, type IM.template.update.g.
3. Click the Design button on the tool bar of the 'Forms Designer' tab.
4. Click the Site Category combo box.
5. In the Properties section, scroll down and visualize the editable 'Value List' property, which contains the values recommended for siteCategory. The default values are\: A, B, C, D and remote.
